default&#xa0;
defaultCWA was established in 2003 as the direct representative body of Scotland’s community woodland groups. We help community woodland groups across the country achieve their aspirations and potential, providing advice, assistance and information, facilitating 
defaultnetworking and training, and representing and promoting community woodlands to the wider world. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe first community land buyout in Scotland was at 
defaultWooplaw
default Community Woodland in the Borders (1987), and there are now well over 200 community woodland groups
default across Scotland, responsible for the management of tens of thousands of hectares of woodland and open space.
default 
defaultMore than half of our members own their woods, the remainder lease or work in partnership with public and private sector landowners.
default 
defaultCommunity w
defaultoodlands are extremely diverse, embracing all woodland types from ancient semi-natural woods to extensive conifer plantations, and ranging from less than a hectare to 
defaultover a thousand hectares in size
default.
default 
defaultLikewise, the communities involved range from 
defaultcrofting
default townships in the far north and west to small towns and inner-city communities in the central belt.
defaultSome of the larger groups employ staff to manage and develop their woods, while others are managed entirely by volunteers.
default 
defaultWhilst the aims and objectives 
defaultof individual groups vary according to local needs and aspirations, and the type and scale of the woodland managed, all are working to build sustainable, flourishing, creative, resilient and vibrant communities.
default 
defaultScotland’s community woodlands deliver a hu
defaultge range of public benefits, 
defaultacross a suite of policy agendas, 
defaultincluding:
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the past decade we have supported a great many of our member
default groups
default in their attempts to acquire land
default, from private and publi
defaultc sector
default landowners.
default 
defaultSome are successful; 
defaultalmost all discover that the process of 
defaultacquisition 
defaultis onerous, bureaucratic and long-winded.
default 
defaultIssues around valuation and financing have proved particularly difficult, in part at least as a consequence of the dis
defaulttorted market in and inflated price of land caused by the favourable tax and subsidy regime for landowners.
