defaultAnnex 3default              defaultStadefaultte Aiddefault&#xa0;defaultState Aid refers to forms of assistance from a public body, or publicly-funded body, given to selected undertakings (any entity whic
defaulth puts goods or services on the given market), which ha
defaultve
default the potential to distort competition and affect trade between member states of the European Union.
default These 
defaultrules were designed to protect the operation of the free market and to facilitate a level pla
defaultying field for major commercial interests with the capacity to trade across member states of the European Union; it seems 
defaultunlikely
default that they were intend to inhibit the regeneration of some of our most disadvantaged communities or to restrict the growth
default and
default operation
default of locally based, not for profit social 
defaultenterprises.
default&#xa0;
defaultFor an investment to be considered a state aid it must satisfy all of the following criteria: the support must be from state resources, confer a selective advantage, have the potential to dis
defaulttort competition, and affect trade between Member States. Where investments are assessed to be a state aid, 
defaultsupport to an
default organisation is capped at 200,000 euro in a rolling three year period.
default 
defaultAny additional investment beyond this 
defaultde 
defaultminimis
default level can onl
defaulty be made
default through approved schemes or
