default(vi) The burden of working with the State Aid rules can be substantial for cdefaultommunity groupsdefaultWhilst i
defaultt is the responsibility of the awarding organisation to inform the recipient that aid is being awarded through th
defaulte
default 
defaultde 
defaultminimis
default pr
defaultovision,
default it is the responsibility of the recipient organisation to maintain a current rolling total of t
defaulthe amount of such assistance received from all sources over a 3 year period, and to inform sources of possible further aid, should the threshold be likely to be breached.
default 
defaultThis can represent a substantial administrative burden, not least because the thresh
defaultold is expressed in Euros, and different awards will have different exchange rates applied.
default 
defaultCommunity organisations generally have high standards of governance and these liabilities are taken seriously, and often discourage a group from pursuing a project
default even when funding is available- or because of the risk it will prevent them from pursuing other projects.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe note
default that local authorities and some public 
defaultagenc
defaulties, who are eligible to apply 
defaultto public funds
default such as LEADER, have been able to sidestep 
defaultthis s
defaulttage of 
defaultState Aid appraisal by refusing to provide details of previous funding, on the grounds that their organisations don’t keep comprehensive records.
default 
defaultThe complexity of State Aid issues and the need to ensure compliance in order to receive commercial f
defaultinance has contributed to spiralling 'due diligence’ costs from commercial lenders. These are effectively an overhead that the community must include in its project costs, but as they can reach six figures for sub-million pound projects, they represent a s
defaultignificant financial burden and mean that projects must be over a certain minimum size to access this form of finance.
